    <div id="explanation">
        <h2>Explanation: Recursion Depth Limits and Risks</h2>
        <p>Recursion is a powerful technique for solving problems that can be broken down into smaller sub-problems of the same type. However, it comes with risks, particularly the risk of a stack overflow. Each recursive call adds a layer to the system's call stack, and if the recursion is too deep, it can exceed the maximum stack size, leading to a crash.</p>
        <p>In the case of drawing a fractal tree, the recursion depth directly affects the complexity of the tree. A higher recursion depth results in a more detailed tree but also increases the risk of a stack overflow.</p>
        <p>For practical applications, especially when dealing with user input for recursion depth, it's often better to implement iterative solutions instead of recursive ones to avoid stack overflow risks. Iterative solutions use a loop instead of function calls, which doesn't add layers to the call stack.</p>
        <p>This example uses recursion for simplicity and educational purposes. For a production environment or when dealing with high recursion depths, consider converting the recursive function to an iterative one.</p>
    </div>

    <script>
        const canvas = document.getElementById('canvas');
        const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
        const slider = document.getElementById('slider');
        const depthSpan = document.getElementById('depth');

        slider.addEventListener('input', () => {
            depthSpan.textContent = slider.value;
            drawTree(parseInt(slider.value));
        });

        function drawTree(depth) {
            ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);
            ctx.translate(canvas.width / 2, canvas.height);
            ctx.strokeStyle = 'black';
            ctx.lineWidth = 2;
            drawBranch(200, -Math.PI / 2, depth);
        }

        function drawBranch(length, angle, depth) {
            if (depth === 0) return;

            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.moveTo(0, 0);
            ctx.lineTo(length * Math.cos(angle), length * Math.sin(angle));
            ctx.stroke();

            ctx.save();
            ctx.translate(length * Math.cos(angle), length * Math.sin(angle));
            ctx.rotate(angle - Math.PI / 6);
            drawBranch(length * 0.67, 0, depth - 1);
            ctx.restore();

            ctx.save();
            ctx.translate(length * Math.cos(angle), length * Math.sin(angle));
            ctx.rotate(angle + Math.PI / 6);
            drawBranch(length * 0.67, 0, depth - 1);
            ctx.restore();
        }

        // Initial draw
        drawTree(6);
    </script>
